The last digit of \( n \) is determined by the sum of factorials from \( 1! \) to \( 10! \). Since \( 5! = 120 \) and all higher factorials end with 0, only \( 1! + 2! + 3! + 4! = 1 + 2 + 6 + 24 = 33 \) contributes to the last digit, so \( n \) ends in 3.  
The last digit of \( 3^3 = 27 \) is 7, and because the exponent \( n \) is odd and ends in 3, the last digit of \( n^n \) cycles with powers of 3 (3, 9, 7, 1) and for an exponent ending in 3 gives 7.  

